    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you don't see any bugs, it's likely a nutrient issue, and checking the soil pH is a great place to start. You can use a soil testing kit to get an idea of the pH levels in your soil. But, just like a goblin might be hiding in a hidden cave, the pH levels might be off by a small margin, making it difficult to detect.\n\nTo get an accurate reading, you can also collect a soil sample and send it to a lab for analysis. This will give you a more precise reading of the pH levels and nutrient content. But, if you're short on time, a DIY kit can give you a good starting point.\n\nAnother thing to consider is the type of soil you're using. If your soil is heavy clay or sandy, it might not be holding onto the nutrients as well as you'd like. This is like trying to find a goblin's treasure trove - it's hidden in plain sight, but you need to know where to look.\n\nIn terms of adjusting the pH, if your soil is too acidic, you can add lime to raise the pH. But, if your soil is too alkaline, you'll need to add sulfur. It's a bit like trying to",
